   <text>
      <body>
         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers2083">
               <p>The son of French Roman Catholics, Valton was born in
                     <placeName>London</placeName> while his father was serving as a page in the
                  Court of <persName>George II</persName>. Valton converted to Protestantism in
                     <date when="1753">1753</date>, trained as an accountant, and served for several
                  years in various ordnance posts. While at <placeName>Purfleet</placeName> he was
                  drawn into the Methodist society and converted in <date when="1764">1764</date>.
                  He became active in various forms of local ministry, and in <date when="1775"
                     >1775</date> resigned his government post to become a <seg ana="itinerancy"
                     >traveling preacher</seg>, serving for 13 years. He married <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers1671.xml"/>Judith (Davis) Purnell</persName> on <date
                     when="1786-12-30">Dec. 30, 1786</date>, in <placeName>Bristol</placeName> and
                  settled there. See Atmore, <hi rend="italic">Memorial</hi>, 431–36; <hi
                     rend="italic">DEB</hi>, 1133; <hi rend="italic">EMP</hi>, 6:1–136; <hi
                     rend="italic">Minutes</hi> (post-Wesley, 1794), 1:296; and Vickers, <hi
                     rend="italic">Dictionary</hi>, 362.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
   </text>
